    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the Enneagram?</summary>
        <p>The Enneagram is a personality system that describes nine distinct types, each defined by a core motivation, a core fear, and a characteristic pattern of thinking, feeling, and behaving. The word comes from the Greek ennea (nine) and gramma (something drawn), referring to the nine-pointed geometric figure that maps the relationships between the types. Unlike frameworks that focus on observable behavior, the Enneagram focuses on the internal motivations that drive behavior. <a href="/test/enneagram-test/">Take our free Enneagram Test</a> to discover your type.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do Enneagram wings work?</summary>
        <p>Wings are the two types that sit on either side of your core type on the Enneagram circle. Most people lean toward one wing more than the other, and this wing adds a distinct flavor to their core type. For example, a Type 1 with a 9 wing (1w9) tends to be more idealistic and reserved, while a Type 1 with a 2 wing (1w2) tends to be more warm and action-oriented. Both are fundamentally Type 1s driven by the same core motivation, but the wing influences how that core type is expressed.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can your Enneagram type change?</summary>
        <p>Enneagram theory holds that your core type does not change over the course of your lifetime. Your fundamental motivation and fear remain the same. However, you can experience tremendous growth within your type by moving toward healthier expressions, integrating the positive qualities of your growth arrow, and developing your wings. Personal development in the Enneagram is not about becoming a different type but about becoming the healthiest, most integrated version of the type you already are.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the Enneagram centers?</summary>
        <p>The nine types are grouped into three centers of intelligence. The Body Center (Types 8, 9, and 1) processes through instinct and gut feeling, with anger as its underlying emotion. The Heart Center (Types 2, 3, and 4) processes through emotion and image, with shame as its underlying emotion. The Head Center (Types 5, 6, and 7) processes through analysis and planning, with fear as its underlying emotion. Your center influences how you fundamentally engage with the world.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is the Enneagram different from MBTI?</summary>
        <p>The <a href="/blog/understanding-16-personality-types/">MBTI</a> describes how you interact with the world based on cognitive preferences like Extraversion/Introversion and Thinking/Feeling. The Enneagram focuses on why you do what you do by identifying your core motivation and core fear. Two people with the same MBTI type can have completely different Enneagram types because their underlying motivations differ. The two systems complement each other well: the MBTI maps your cognitive style, while the Enneagram maps your emotional and motivational landscape.</p>
      </details>
